WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.680
I forgot the right button this time.

00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:07.400
So I'll be presenting on antibody drug conjugates targeting TRBC1 and TRBC2.

00:00:07.820 --> 00:00:13.340
This is all preclinical at this point and led by a colleague of mine at Johns Hopkins,

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:18.700
Shuman Paul, and wanted to highlight some of this work and potential use for some of

00:00:18.700 --> 00:00:19.600
our patients in the future.

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:23.940
Here are my disclosures and objectives.

00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:32.060
So as a very brief review, TCR receptor diversity comes from genetic recombination from the

00:00:32.060 --> 00:00:33.500
alpha chain and the beta chain.

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:39.500
We have these VD and J gene segments rearranged, which allow for the variable region.

00:00:40.100 --> 00:00:46.600
And then we also have two constant regions, at least on the beta chain, that end up allowing

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:48.540
for a mature T cell receptor.

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:55.700
We know that each T cell, whether it's mature normal T cell or a mature malignant,

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:58.080
T cell, will have a unique TCR.

00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:04.240
And most of these, about 95% will be alpha beta, a small subset will be gamma delta.

00:01:04.920 --> 00:01:09.260
But this has important therapeutic implications in terms of potential targets.

00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:16.040
Since each clone will have a gene segment that's represented from only one of these

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:20.480
variable regions, there are approximately 30, depending on how you define these in various

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:20.880
studies.

00:01:21.380 --> 00:01:25.600
But we initially looked at this, and Dr. Paul looked at this, targeting.

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:33.660
One of these variable regions for various T cell lymphoma cell lines, and seeing if

00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:39.300
we could deplete the clone, while also depleting only a small subset of the otherwise healthy

00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:39.920
T cells.

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:43.480
This approach was effective in preclinical evaluation.

00:01:44.140 --> 00:01:48.440
But from a practical standpoint, the concern is we would theoretically have to develop 30

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:51.900
drugs for what is otherwise already a very rare disease.

00:01:53.500 --> 00:01:55.680
The other option is to target the constant.

00:01:55.720 --> 00:01:59.860
Regions we know that we have constant region one and constant region two, each clone

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:05.360
representing one of these two options with the potential to deplete essentially half of the

00:02:05.360 --> 00:02:11.980
healthy T cells in the all 100% of hopefully of the malignant T cells.

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:19.640
This approach has been evaluated clinically with a TRBC1 targeted CAR-T cell therapy coming

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:20.720
out of the London group.

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:24.960
This was the auto four study, a total of 10 patients that were evaluated.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:25.720
Of the.

00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:33.040
These five patients achieved a complete response and initially very promising activity.

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:37.280
But the concern is most of these patients ultimately relapsed.

00:02:37.280 --> 00:02:42.480
And at one year, there were only two patients that were alive and without relapse and further

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:47.360
evaluation realized essentially all of the CAR-T cells had been killed off.

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:55.340
And the concern was that it was this lack of CAR-T persistence allowing for the escape of the T cell malignancy.

00:02:55.720 --> 00:03:05.560
In a paper we published a couple of years ago, we evaluated potential explanations and mechanisms for this led by Dr.

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:08.680
Paul, and there are a few of these.

00:03:08.680 --> 00:03:25.540
And one of these, I think the one that is perhaps most well established is the concept of fratricide that if we're giving a CAR-T product that is targeting TRBC1 and the product itself includes TRBC1 positive CAR-T cells, they can kill each other off.

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:36.920
There's also the concern of the non-CAR-T cells, the normal healthy T cells and the malignant T cells that are engaged at the time of the CAR-T cell coming into contact with them.

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:43.960
And while the CAR-T becomes activated, the normal T cells also become activated and there's this bi-directional killing that occurs.

00:03:45.460 --> 00:03:55.680
So because of this, we evaluated a, an anti-TRBC1 ADC approach, slightly different target, but also in TRBC1, and the concept being that we.

00:03:55.680 --> 00:04:03.720
could again deplete approximately 50% of the healthy T cells and 100% hopefully of the malignant T cells.

